<h1>Online Bible: New World Translation of the Holy Scriptures</h1>
</noscript>
<p class="title">Ruth 1:1-22</p>
<form class="formtext">
<input type="hidden" name="chapterCount" value="4">
<input type="hidden" name="verseCount" value="22">
<p><a name="bk1" class="vsAnchor">1</a>
       <span id="vs1">Now it came about in the days when the judges administered justice that a famine arose in the land, and a man proceeded to go from Beth&acute;le&middot;hem in Judah to reside as an alien in the fields of Mo&acute;ab, he with his wife and his two sons.</span> <a name="bk2" class="vsAnchor">2</a>
       <span id="vs2">And the man’s name was E&middot;lim&acute;e&middot;lech, and his wife’s name Na&acute;o&middot;mi, and the names of his two sons were Mah&acute;lon and Chil&acute;i&middot;on, Eph&acute;rath&middot;ites from Beth&acute;le&middot;hem in Judah. Eventually they came to the fields of Mo&acute;ab and continued there.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk3" class="vsAnchor">3</a>
       <span id="vs3">In time E&middot;lim&acute;e&middot;lech the husband of Na&acute;o&middot;mi died, so that she remained with her two sons.</span> <a name="bk4" class="vsAnchor">4</a>
       <span id="vs4">Later the men took wives for themselves, Mo&acute;ab&middot;ite women. The name of the one was Or&acute;pah, and the name of the other Ruth. And they went on dwelling there for about ten years.</span> <a name="bk5" class="vsAnchor">5</a>
       <span id="vs5">In time the two of them, Mah&acute;lon and Chil&acute;i&middot;on, also died, so that the woman remained without her two children and her husband.</span> <a name="bk6" class="vsAnchor">6</a>
       <span id="vs6">And she proceeded to get up with her daughters-in-law and to return from the fields of Mo&acute;ab, for she had heard in the field of Mo&acute;ab that Jehovah had turned his attention to his people by giving them bread.</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk7" class="vsAnchor">7</a>
       <span id="vs7">And she went her way out from the place where she had continued, and both of her daughters-in-law were with her, and they kept walking on the road to return to the land of Judah.</span> <a name="bk8" class="vsAnchor">8</a>
       <span id="vs8">Finally Na&acute;o&middot;mi said to both of her daughters-in-law: “Go, return, each one to the house of her mother. May Jehovah exercise loving-kindness toward <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>, just as <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> have exercised it toward the men now dead and toward me.</span> <a name="bk9" class="vsAnchor">9</a>
       <span id="vs9">May Jehovah make a gift to <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>, and do <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> find a resting-place each one in the house of her husband.” Then she kissed them, and they began to raise their voices and weep.</span> <a name="bk10" class="vsAnchor">10</a>
       <span id="vs10">And they kept saying to her: “No, but with you we shall return to your people.”</span> <a name="bk11" class="vsAnchor">11</a>
       <span id="vs11">But Na&acute;o&middot;mi said: “Return, my daughters. Why should <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> go with me? Do I still have sons in my inward parts, and will they have to become <span class="smallcaps">YOUR</span> husbands?</span> <a name="bk12" class="vsAnchor">12</a>
       <span id="vs12">Return, my daughters, go, for I have grown too old to get to belong to a husband. If I had said I had hope also that I should certainly become a husband’s tonight and also should certainly bear sons,</span> <a name="bk13" class="vsAnchor">13</a>
       <span id="vs13">would <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> keep waiting for them until they could grow up? Would <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> keep yourselves secluded for them so as not to become a husband’s? No, my daughters, for it is very bitter to me because of <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span>, that the hand of Jehovah has gone out against me.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk14" class="vsAnchor">14</a>
       <span id="vs14">At that they raised their voices and wept some more, after which Or&acute;pah kissed her mother-in-law. As for Ruth, she stuck with her.</span> <a name="bk15" class="vsAnchor">15</a>
       <span id="vs15">So she said: “Look! Your widowed sister-in-law has returned to her people and her gods. Return with your widowed sister-in-law.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk16" class="vsAnchor">16</a>
       <span id="vs16">And Ruth proceeded to say: “Do not plead with me to abandon you, to turn back from accompanying you; for where you go I shall go, and where you spend the night I shall spend the night. Your people will be my people, and your God my God.</span> <a name="bk17" class="vsAnchor">17</a>
       <span id="vs17">Where you die I shall die, and there is where I shall be buried. May Jehovah do so to me and add to it if anything but death should make a separation between me and you.”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk18" class="vsAnchor">18</a>
       <span id="vs18">When she got to see that she was persistent about going with her, then she left off speaking to her.</span> <a name="bk19" class="vsAnchor">19</a>
       <span id="vs19">And they both continued on their way until they came to Beth&acute;le&middot;hem. And it came about that as soon as they came to Beth&acute;le&middot;hem, all the city became stirred up over them, and the women kept saying: “Is this Na&acute;o&middot;mi?”</span> <a name="bk20" class="vsAnchor">20</a>
       <span id="vs20">And she would say to the women: “Do not call me Na&acute;o&middot;mi. Call me Ma&acute;ra, for the Almighty has made it very bitter for me.</span> <a name="bk21" class="vsAnchor">21</a>
       <span id="vs21">I was full when I went, and it is empty-handed that Jehovah has made me return. Why should <span class="smallcaps">YOU</span> call me Na&acute;o&middot;mi, when it is Jehovah that has humiliated me and the Almighty that has caused me calamity?”</span>
</p>

<p><a name="bk22" class="vsAnchor">22</a>
       <span id="vs22">Thus Na&acute;o&middot;mi made her return, Ruth the Mo&acute;ab&middot;ite woman, her daughter-in-law, being with her when returning from the fields of Mo&acute;ab; and they came to Beth&acute;le&middot;hem at the commencement of barley harvest.</span>
</p>
</form>

